      <text>
        Oakshade wasn't kidding—the second day is steeper. This morning's climb is less "gentle hill" and more "why is this path vertical?" The terrain is rougher—exposed rock faces, narrow ledges, places where I have to use my hands to pull myself up. My legs are already sore from yesterday, and now they're discovering whole new categories of "ow."

        Oakshade advises, "Breathe slowly — thin air requires patience."

        My lungs agree. Every breath feels like it's doing less work than it should.

        Mossmantle says, "Three more meters, then rest — flat ledge ahead. Good footing."

        I count the meters—one, two, three—then the ledge appears, blessedly flat, and I collapse onto it.

        Scout bounces up beside me, not even winded—show-off.

        Oakshade says, "We're close now." There's something different in their voice—reverence, maybe.

        Oakshade says, "Elder Heartwood's grove is beyond the next ridge."

        I ask, "Really?"

        Mossmantle says quietly, "You'll know it when you see it. Everyone does."

        We climb the final ridge—then they're right; I know it immediately.

        ¶

        The valley below is… enormous. Not just big—_vast_. Filling most of it is a single tree. No, that's wrong—it's not a tree. It's… I don't even have the right words.

        Elder Heartwood is massive beyond any scale I've ever experienced. The trunk must be hundreds of meters across—so wide it takes me several seconds to process that it's one organism, not a forest. Branches spread like networks, each one thick enough to be a tree itself. The canopy covers the entire valley, creating a perpetual twilight beneath. And the roots—oh, the roots. They don't just anchor the tree; they are the landscape—raised ridges running everywhere, diving underground and surfacing again, creating natural paths and terraces and structures.

        It's alive and also architecture, ecosystem and individual, ancient in a way that makes my spine tingle.

        I whisper, "How old?"

        Oakshade says simply, "Old — before cities, before networks, before language as we know it."

        That doesn't really answer the question, but maybe there isn't a good answer. How do you measure something that's been growing since before anyone was counting?

        Mossmantle says gently, "Come — the presenting ground is this way."

        We descend into the valley. The air changes—thicker somehow, rich with the scent of wood and earth and something else I can't identify—time, maybe. The grove is quiet—not silent; there are sounds: wind through massive branches, small creatures moving through the understory, water trickling somewhere. It's a particular kind of quiet, the kind that makes you want to whisper.

        Scout has stopped bouncing, rolling alongside me, subdued. Even Scout feels it.
      </text>
