        The presenting ground is a cleared space at the base of Elder Heartwood's trunk—a broad, circular platform where the roots create natural seating all around the edges. The ground is covered in soft moss that glows faintly with bioluminescence—beautiful and completely unexpected.

        And we are not alone.

        Three other plant beings are already here: one looks like a massive fungal bloom—shelf after shelf of growth spiraling up into a column. Another is all flowing vines, constantly moving. The third is something I can't even categorize—crystalline and plant and something in between.

        They turn as we approach.

        The fungal being says, "Another question-bearer. Welcome to the presenting ground."
        Their voice is layered—like multiple organisms speaking in harmony.

        Oakshade introduces us, "We have come to ask Elder Heartwood about human survival needs—this is Kira Voss, the human we are assisting."

        The vine being flows closer, inspecting me with what might be curiosity. "Fascinating. Small. Very mobile. Yes, I can see why you'd have questions."

        I ask, "How long have you been waiting?"

        The crystalline being replies, "Seventeen days. Elder Heartwood considers deeply."

        Seventeen days— and they are just waiting… patient as stones.

        The fungal being notices my expression and explains, "The wait is part of the wisdom—Elder Heartwood's answers are worth waiting for."

        I want to ask if they're sure about that, but it feels rude. Also, I'm surrounded by beings who've been waiting seventeen days for wisdom, standing in a glowing circle at the base of an impossibly ancient tree. Skepticism feels inappropriate here.

        Oakshade moves to the center of the platform, branches spreading wide, and presents the question: "We present our question to Elder Heartwood."
        The words feel formal—ceremonial. This is clearly a ritual.

        Oakshade continues, "A human has come to our territory—not by choice, but by accident. We wish to help, but our frameworks don't match. We've learned from her, she's learned from us, but gaps remain. How do we properly care for a being so different from ourselves? What do humans need that we haven't yet understood? How do we bridge incompatible frameworks?"

        The words echo in the quiet grove—I didn't expect a reply—but I feel something—like the space is listening. Actually paying attention in a way that's more than just sound waves hitting bark.

        ¶

        Then the ground shifts.

        Not violently. Not even alarmingly. Just movement—the roots beneath us flex, settling into a new position like someone shifting weight to get comfortable before thinking.

        The fungal being announces, "Elder Heartwood acknowledges—the question is received."

        A deep groan resonates through the valley—so low I feel it in my chest before I hear it. It lasts several seconds, then fades. Was that agreement? Understanding? Just mechanical movement of ancient wood?

        I don't know, but the plants around me seem satisfied.
      </text>
