        Mossmantle says, "Now we wait."

        I ask, "How long?"

        Oakshade says, "Weeks—months, perhaps. Elder Heartwood thinks in seasons, not days."

        Months—*we might be waiting months for an answer.*

        The vine plant says, "But the answer will be worth it. Elder Heartwood understands connections, frameworks, bridges between incompatible systems. If anyone can tell you how to care for your human, it's Elder Heartwood."

        The certainty in the plants' voices is absolute. They don't just hope Elder Heartwood will help—they *know* it. This is their ultimate authority, their ancient counsel, the one who understands what no one else can.

        And I want to believe them—I do. Standing here in this twilight grove, feeling the immensity of something so old it predates language, hearing that deep groan of acknowledgment—I want to trust that wisdom this ancient might actually have answers.

        ¶

        Oakshade and Mossmantle are both still—attentive, reverent. They presented the question beautifully, framed it perfectly. And Elder Heartwood received it.

        Scout rolls closer and bumps against my ankle. I reach down and rest my hand on their sphere. We're in this together, waiting for wisdom from an ancient tree.

        I ask quietly, "What happens now?"

        The fungal being says, "Now you return home. Resume your life. Elder Heartwood considers your question, draws on countless seasons of experience, connects patterns you cannot see. When the understanding is ready, the answer will come."

        The crystalline plant adds, "And it will help—Elder Heartwood's wisdom always helps."

        Always—absolute certainty.

        Buddy, who has been quiet until now, speaks softly in my mind: "Kira, this is remarkable! Ancient wisdom consultation is a well-documented decision-making framework. Anthropological studies show that—"

        I cut him off. "Buddy, shh. Let me just… be here for a minute."

        "Of course. Apologies."

        I stand in the glowing circle under the canopy of something impossibly old and try to feel hopeful.

        The journey here taught me a lot—nine days of walking, three territories, three guide pairs. I learned to trust the process, found my own competence, and discovered that plants speak different languages I can learn.

        But underneath those real lessons we've been building toward this—the question to end questions, the wisdom that will actually explain how to care for me, how to bridge the gap between human needs and plant understanding.

        And maybe—probably?—it will.

        Elder Heartwood has lived for an incomprehensible span of time—surely that counts for something; surely wisdom that deep can see what we're missing.

        Oakshade asks, "Ready to return?"

        I say, "Yeah—I'm ready."

        We leave the presenting ground. Scout takes one last look back at the massive trunk, paying respects or simply standing awed, like I am.

        The climb out of the valley is quieter than the descent. We're all thinking, processing, hoping.
      </text>
